                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-defend1501" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18270531-273-off1474" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-off1474" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-off1474" type="offenceSubcategory" value="grandLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18270531-273-cd1475" type="crimeDate">30th of May</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-273-off1474 t18270531-273-cd1475"></join>, 1 quart of wine, value 2s., and 1 bottle, value 2d
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18270531-273-victim1502" type="victimName">
                  William 
                  Pudney
               <interp inst="t18270531-273-victim1502" type="surname" value="Pudney"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-victim1502" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-victim1502" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-273-off1474 t18270531-273-victim1502"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>WILLIAM PUDNEY. I <rs id="t18270531-273-viclabel1476" type="occupation">keep the <placeName id="t18270531-273-crimeloc1477">Three Johns public-house, at Pentonville</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-crimeloc1477" type="placeName" value="Three Johns public-house, at Pentonville"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-crimeloc1477" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-273-off1474 t18270531-273-crimeloc1477"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-273-victim1502 t18270531-273-viclabel1476"></join>. On the 29th of May I left the key in the wine cellar-door; I went down, and missed one bottle from a bin which I had seen safe that morning, it had laid very smooth, and if a bottle was gone I should know it; the wine had been there for six months; the prisoner was my pot-boy, and had access to that cellar; on the day following I left the key in the door on purpose, when he was going down to fetch a pail of water - I afterwards went into my bed-room, and saw him, (while he was washing his pots,) pour some wine out of a bottle, into a pint pot, and drink it - I had before this seen the bottle in the wash-house - I went down, and the bottle was gone - I told my wife; she said, "I will call him to tea;" I then went down again, and found the same bottle filled with gin - I fetched a constable; and he denied the whole of it- I knew the bottle by these two distinct marks of mud on it, which it got in the cellar.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. QUIN. Q. But if your bottles had been elewhere, might they not have got some dirt on them? A. Yes - I missed the bottle on the evening of the day he drank the wine; I told him I was going out for an hour, and then I went to my bed-room; I saw it empty after he drank the wine, and I then missed it for about three minutes.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Do you mean, that while you went to speak to your wife about the constable, it was filled with gin? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been there but two days; he said he had had a young man who had robbed him, and he should be very strict upon me - I said he might; this bottle of gin had been in the cellar nine months or more, and having a few words with my master, he got it up and accused me of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270531-273-person1503">
                  WILLIAM 
                  PUDNEY
               <interp inst="t18270531-273-person1503" type="surname" value="PUDNEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-person1503" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-273-person1503" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . He had a few words the night before, with my wife, because he got tipsy, and could not settle his beer.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q. Did the pint pot hold all the wine? A. There was one-half the wine gone out of the bottle at twelve o'clock, and the remainder he drank out of the pot - I had a good character with him.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 20.</p>
